full_text: @JessMolina @waikato It's amazing what a supportive city can do to a person. I feel like 'growing up' in Hamilton gave me such a safe space to be me. But the best part is the people. Some of the most spectacular people I've ever met, I met through the #lovethetron tag on Twitter.
user.name: #HamiltonHumans/@dileepa_fonseka

full_text: @JessMolina @waikato Hamilton feels more like home now than Manila was. I think it's because I feel like I grew into the person who I wanted to be in Hamilton. I started dressing how I've always wanted to, grew my blog, became a magazine editor, organised @PechaKuchaHtown, did a lot of acting.

full_text: @JessMolina @waikato I got used to it. Started loving the quiet. At 18, I wasn't sure what or who I wanted to be yet but it felt liberating to feel in control. I never used to take public transport or go to public places by myself so the first time I took the bus to town was such an experience!

full_text: @JessMolina @waikato Hamilton slowly started feeling like home. I wasn't sure I'd survive there because I was used to big cities and concrete jungles. I was used to things being open until midnight, coffee shop visits at 3 am, shopping until 11 pm on a weeknight kinda thing. It was a big adjustment.

full_text: @JessMolina @waikato I moved to NZ 2 days before my 18th bday! In Filipino culture, your 18th is the year for the big party so when I got here and realised I didn't know anyone I was shook. Lol. The first few months were rough. We were waiting for our permanent residency so things were in limbo.

full_text: @JessMolina I moved to Hamilton in October 2009 from Manila, Philippines. My dad had been living there for a year, teaching media @waikato, when the rest of the family moved to be together. Most of our family were scattered around NZ and it's always been my parents dream to move here.
